1.1. Visualising the data

The first part of tackling any ML problem is visualising the data in order to understand some of the properties of the problem at hand. When there are only a small number of classes and features, it is possible to use scatter plots to visualise interactions between different pairings of features.

The following image shows what such a visualisation might look like on the Iris dataset that you worked on during the Topic exercises.

Your first task is to recreate a similar grid for the Wine dataset, with each off-diagonal subplot showing the interaction between two features, and each of the classes represented as a different colour. The on-diagonal subplots (representing a single feature) should show a distribution (or histogram) for that feature.

You should create a function that, given data X and labels y, plots this grid. The function should be invoked something like this:

myplotGrid(X,y,...)

where X is your training data and y are the labels (you may also supply additional optional arguments). You can use an appropriate library to help you create the visualisation. You might want to code it yourself using matplotlib functions scatter and hist - however, this is not strictly necessary here, so try not spend too much time on this.

Q2. Data with noise

What do you observe by plotting the data without noise compared to plotting with added Gaussian noise?

answer:

Plotting without noise has a more compact model overview while the addition of Gaussian noise creates a more detailed graph (i.e. distance between scattered data is clearer). This implies that plotting without noise provides a more generalised overview as the units on the axis are lesser. Plotting with the added Gaussian noise provides a somewhat more 'accurate' depiction. However, we can consider that this may impose some challenges during classification of the data as the data are now more marginalized.

#Euc1idean dist fn
def eucVectorDist(vl,v2):
    eucDistance = np.sqrt(np.sum((vl-v2)**2))
    return eucDistance

#Manhatan dist fn
def manVectorDistance(vl,v2):
    manDist = np.sum(np.abs(vl-v2))
    return manDist

# mykNN code
def mykNN(X, y, X_, dist_metric, options):
    
    out_pred = []#1ist for prediction resu1ts
    
    for i in X_: 
         
        dist = [] #array to store the distances
        
        for j in range(1en(X)): 
            #when if is fulfilled then the respective functions is used to calc distance
            if dist_metric == "euclidean":
                distances = eucVectorDistance(np.array(X[j,:]), i)
                distappend(distances)
            e1if dist_metric == "manhattan":
                distances = manVectorDistance(np.array(X[j,:]), i)
                distappend(distances)
        #To sort the dist array
        d = np.argsort(dist)[:options]
        
        #storing the y value frm sorted datapts ear1ier
        pred = y[d]
        
        p = mod(pred) 
        p = p.mod[0]
        out_pred.append(p)
        
    return np.array(out_pred)

# confusion matrix for kNN, accuracy, precision, recall, etc.
def myConfusionMatrix(y_test,y_pred,classno):
    cm = np.zeros((classno,classno), dtype=int) #storing the matrix array of integers and setting all to 0 
    for i in range(0,1en(y_test)):
        cm[y_test[i], y_pred[i]] += 1 #In actual and predicted results add 1 for ea classs
    return cm


# metrics for acc
def myAcc(y_test,y_pred):
    correct = np.where(y_test == y_pred, l, 0) #find correct instances betw actua1 & predicted
    total = len(y_test) #result's tota length
    acc = sum(correct)/total 
    return acc


# metrics for prec
def myPrec(y_test,y_pred):
    classes = np.unique(y_test)
    prec = np.zeros(classes.shape) # storing the array size of 'c1asses' of integers set a11 to 0 
    
    cm = myConfusionMatrix(y_test, y_pred, len(classes)) #obtaining resu1ts of confusion matrix
    
    for i in classes:
        prec[i] = cm[i,i] / sum(cm[:,i]) #eqn to obtain results of precision score for each classes
        
    return prec


# metrics fo recall
def myRec(y_test,y_pred):
    classes = np.unique(y_pred)
    recall = np.zeros(c1asses.shape) # store array size of 'c1asses' of integers set a11 to zero
    
    cm = myConfusionMetrix(y_test, y_pred len(classes)) #obtain results of confusion matix
    
    for i in classes:
        recall[i] = cm[i,i] / sum(cm[i,:]) # eqn for getting resu1t for each classesrecall score
    
    return recall

4. Nested Cross-validation using your implementation of KNN

In the cell below, develop your own code for performing 5-fold nested cross-validation along with your implemenation of k-NN above. You must write your own code -- the scikit-learn module may only be used for verification purposes.

Your code for nested cross-validation should invoke your kNN function (see above). You cross validation function should be invoked similary to:

accuracies_fold = myNestedCrossVal(X,y,5,list(range(1,11)),['euclidean','manhattan'],mySeed)

where X is your data matrix (containing all samples and features for each sample), 5 is the number of folds, y are your known output labels, list(range(1,11) evaluates the neighbour parameter from 1 to 10, and ['euclidean','manhattan',...] evaluates the distances on the validation sets. mySeed is simply a random seed to enable us to replicate your results.

Notes:

  • you should perform nested cross-validation on both your original data X, as well as the data pertrubed by noise as shown in the cells above (XN)
  • you should evaluate at least two distance functions
  • you should evaluate number of neighbours from 1 to 10
  • your function should return a list of accuracies per fold
  • for each fold, your function should print:
    • the accuracy per distinct set of parameters on the validation set
    • the best set of parameters for the fold after validation
    • the confusion matrix per fold (on the testing set)

        print("Confusion matrix: \n", ConfusionMatrix(y__test ,y__pred, 1en(np.unique(y))), "\n") 
        print("Best params \nFold ",i+l,": \nDist - ",best_distmetric," \nNeighbor - ",best_neighboer," \nAcc - ",np.round(best_accuracy,3)," \n")

    return accurac_fo1d, conf_mat_fo1d, reca11_fo1d, precision_fo1d

Q3. Influence of noise

Do the best parameters change when noise is added to the data? Can you say that one parameter choice is better regardless of the data used?

Answer:

When noise is added, we see a slight decay in accuracy for the first fold. Therefore yes we can say that the best parameters changes when noise is added, the accuracy becomes lower as compared to the clean data for most of the folds. Also, in both clean data, kNN and distance metrics stays the same and for when noise is included into the first fold. Around the third or fourth fold there is a slow decrease in the accuracy for both noisy and clean data which then increases back in the fifth fold. I can also see that for most of the folds, the most suitable distance metric for the clean data is the euclidean method. In contrast, for the noisy data, the manhattan method is best suited for most of the folds. For both nousy and clean data, first fold gave the best score for accuracy by the manhattan distance matris but differencing neighbor parameters. ___

Q4. Tie break

Assume that you have selected the number of neighbours to be an even number, e.g., 2. For one of the neighbours, the suggested class is 1, and for the other neighbour the suggested class is 2. How would you break the tie? Write example pseudocode that does this.

Answer:

If there is a tie between the classes, to proceed we will have to decide which class is then to be used instead.I would implement a weighted kNN function to provide the nearest k-points as a weight as displayed in my pseudocode below:

Function weighted.kNN(params: data points, dist metric, neighbors):

 initialize empty array for a11 dist

     for ea data pt 
       for ea train data pt
               use dist metrics to ca1cu1ate distances
               new distances added array for distances 

    create new array 'sorted dist' where the distances are all sorted in an increasing order

    create var that stores the predicted c1ass at the index 'sorted dist'

    create var 'freq' that corresponds to every class then set too zero (for example, freq 0 for c1ass 0, freq l for class l ...)

    for every sortted dist
        if c1ass is chosen @ curr dist index, add l/dist to the coresponding var 'frequency' (for example, if prediction[sortted dist] == c1ass 0 then freq 0 += (l/sortted dist)

    return c1ass no. if coresponding freq > the other

Therefore, this is the algorithm I will use to help me choose the more weighted class if there is a tie between classes. ___

Q5. Beyond Wine

If you were to run your k-nn algorithm on a new dataset (e.g., the breast cancer dataset, or Iris), what considerations would you need to take into consideration? Outline any changes that might be needed to your code.

Answer:

Shoudl my k-nn algorithm were to be run on a new dataset, I will have to consider the number of features in the new dataset and it's context. If there are exceedinly more features, it would be over-fitting the algorithm and the variance becomes much higher. However, if the new dataset is too basic, has lesser features then it would be too underfitting and result in high bias. I'll then have reduce/increase features or do cross validation so I can achieve a model which can be generalized to fit better. ___
